CURASEAL is a leading provider of medical interventional devices that aim to improve the quality of life for patients and help medical professionals in the field of invasive medical treatment achieve the best outcomes. Combining minimally invasive techniques and innovative technology backed by years of extensive research and testing, our products are designed to significantly reduce the risks associated with treatment of anal and rectal fistulas and promote better recovery for patients.

The CURASEAL Anorectal Fistula Plug (CURASEAL AF) is CURASEAL’S next-generation benchmark fistula repair technology that combines internal ostium sealing, tissue engineering and device fixation to improve outcomes in minimally invasive treatments. A sterile, single-use device created for the treatment of anal and rectal fistulas, it is the first fistula implant designed to effectively seal internal openings by providing a collagen scaffold for fistula tract tissue to enhance recovery. It has a seton that drains fistulas during the healing process while simultaneously securing all components of the implant. The CURASEAL AF consists of:
  • CURASEAL AF Disk
  • CURASEAL AF Delivery Catheter
  • CURASEAL AF Collagen Matrices
There are two models of the CURASEAL AF Delivery System: CURASEAL-AF-M1 and CURASEAL-AF-M2. CURASEAL-AF-M1 consists of a smaller CURASEAL AF Disk and collagen Matrices than CURASEAL-AF-M2.

The CURASEAL ® AF closure system is a sterile, single-use device that is designed for the treatment of anal and rectal fistulas. The CURASEAL AF device is delievered using minimally-invasive methods and is secured to the fistula tract by resorbable sutures. The device consists of the silicone Disk, the Sheath and Dilator Catheters, Collagen Matrices and commercially available resorbable sutures. There are two sizes of the CURASEAL AF closure system: M1 and M2. The M1 device consists of smaller diameter silicone Disk/Catheter/Collagen Matrices compared to M2 device (see figures). Other than dimensional differences in the diameters, all lengths and design features remain the same between the M1 and M2 devices.
